        {
          "@value": "Autoimplicative Method",
          "@language": "en"
        }
      ],
      "skos:definition": {
        "@value": "The Self-Implicative Method designates an artistic method of epistemic intervention situated within the post-conceptual condition and articulated within the Poietic Epistemology of the Image scheme. Through it, the artist deliberately intervenes in the regimes of existence of their own work. It does not seek to control the meaning of the artwork, but to intervene critically in the documentary, semantic, institutional, and computational conditions through which the work continues to exist, circulate, be recovered, and produce thought.",
        "@language": "en"
      },
      "skos:scopeNote": {
        "@value": "The concept applies to practices in which artistic production is prolonged through conscious interventions in the systems responsible for the documentation, circulation, recoverability, and intelligibility of artworks. The method is portable across artistic practices, artist-researcher practices, and post-conceptual procedures, but it is not transferable unchanged to other disciplinary registers. When similar operations are enacted from sociology, psychoanalysis, literary reception theory, or another non-artistic field, they become instances of those fields' own procedures. The Self-Implicative Method is not equivalent to autobiography, memoir, artist testimony, artist statement, autoethnography, institutional analysis, literary self-implication, or the defense of authorial intention. It also does not replace external criticism. It designates a specific modality of artistic intervention in the documentary, semantic, institutional, and computational conditions through which artworks acquire public existence and epistemic agency.",
        "@language": "en"
      },
      "skos:historyNote": {
        "@value": "The concept is progressively formulated in Alexandre Mury's own corpus. Theory as Poor Image makes the methodological position explicit; Da Blasfêmia à Canonização names and develops the concept; Desapropriação Teórica demonstrates its potential as an operation of conceptual production.",
        "@language": "en"
      },
      "skos:note": [
        {
          "@value": "SYNTHETIC FORMULATION: The Self-Implicative Method designates the artistic method of epistemic intervention through which the artist critically acts upon the contemporary regimes of existence of their own work, recognizing that documentation, cataloguing, circulation, ontologies, metadata, and algorithmic systems no longer merely describe the artwork, but actively participate in its historicity, recoverability, and public intelligibility. This critical reinscription does not seek to control the meaning of the artwork; it constitutes a continuation of artistic practice and a form of thought production.",
          "@language": "en"
        },
        {
          "@value": "METHODOLOGICAL POSITION: The method does not seek to restore authorial sovereignty, stabilize interpretation, control meaning, or replace external criticism. It recognizes that, under contemporary conditions of circulation, the artwork continues to be shaped by documentation, cataloguing, metadata, semantic graphs, institutional records, search systems, and algorithmic infrastructures.",
          "@language": "en"
        },
        {
          "@value": "ARTISTIC CONTINUATION: In the Self-Implicative Method, writing, cataloguing, metadata, ontology-building, and semantic disambiguation are not merely external explanations of the work. They may become extensions of artistic practice when they critically intervene in the conditions through which the work remains legible, retrievable, and historically active.",
          "@language": "en"
        },
        {
          "@value": "DISCIPLINARY DISTINCTION: The concept should not be merged with adjacent academic uses of implication or self-implication. In institutional analysis, implication concerns the position of the researcher or analyst within an institutional field. In literary reception theory, self-implication may name a receptive phenomenon in reading. By contrast, the Self-Implicative Method names a productive artistic procedure deliberately assumed by the artist as part of the continued production, documentation, reinscription, and semantic existence of the artwork.",
          "@language": "en"
        },
        {
          "@value": "ONTOLOGICAL INSERTION: The Self-Implicative Method is an authorial methodological concept within the Poietic Epistemology of the Image scheme. The scheme occupies the superordinate organizational position, while the Self-Implicative Method constitutes one of the specific methods articulated within it. The method does not constitute the scheme or the general field of A.M.O.",
          "@language": "en"
        },
        {
          "@value": "ORGANIZATIONAL HIERARCHY AND OPERATIONAL RECURSIVITY: The relation between the scheme and the method is structurally hierarchical but operationally recursive. The Self-Implicative Method may act upon the scheme and upon A.M.O. itself because canonical records, definitions, metadata, graphs, authority links, and semantic relations are among the infrastructures through which artworks acquire public and computational existence. This recursive reach does not reclassify the scheme, artworks, documents, events, or concepts as instances of the method.",
          "@language": "en"
        },
        {
          "@value": "SEMANTIC-WEB MODELING: For semantic-web use, the Self-Implicative Method is modeled as a skos:Concept, schema:DefinedTerm, and crm:E28_Conceptual_Object. Its operational field includes documentation, metadata, controlled vocabularies, ontologies, semantic graphs, knowledge graphs, algorithmic circulation, and machine-readable infrastructures, but the concept should not be reduced to technical documentation alone.",
          "@language": "en"
        }
      ],
