      "amo:syntheticFormula": {
        "@value": "The Self-Implicative Method designates the artistic method of epistemic intervention through which the artist critically acts upon the contemporary regimes of existence of their own work, recognizing that documentation, cataloguing, circulation, ontologies, metadata, and algorithmic systems no longer merely describe the artwork, but actively participate in its historicity, recoverability, and public intelligibility. This critical reinscription does not seek to control the meaning of the artwork; it constitutes a continuation of artistic practice and a form of thought production.",
        "@language": "en"
      },
      "schema:disambiguatingDescription": "The Self-Implicative Method is a specific artistic method of epistemic intervention articulated within the Poietic Epistemology of the Image scheme. It is not the scheme itself, a general synonym for implication or self-implication, or an equivalent of autoethnography, institutional analysis, psychoanalysis, literary reception theory, artist statements, or authorial intention.",
      "skos:editorialNote": {
        "@value": "The term should not be merged with adjacent academic uses of implication or self-implication. In René Lourau's L'Analyse institutionnelle (1970), implication belongs to institutional analysis and concerns the position of the researcher or analyst within an institutional field. In Kuiken, Miall, and Sikora's 'Forms of Self-Implication in Literary Reading' (2004), self-implication names a receptive phenomenon in literary reading. By contrast, the Self-Implicative Method names a productive artistic procedure deliberately assumed by the artist as part of the continued production, documentation, reinscription, and semantic existence of the artwork.",
        "@language": "en"
      },
